import streamlit as st

st.title("The Price is Truth")
st.write("***Why the News is Noise and the Chart is Reality***")
st.write("""
Most folks think the stock market is just a big, complicated math problem. They figure if they crunch enough numbers, sit through enough boring earnings calls, or watch enough CNBC, they’ll eventually crack the code and find the "fair value" of a stock. They think if they're smart enough, they can out-calculate the market. \n
Guess what? They’re wrong. And honestly, that's why you see literal rocket scientists losing their shirts on Wall Street while some kid in a basement makes a killing. \n
The market isn't a math problem. It’s a **behavioral psychology graph**. It’s basically a live, pulsing feed of millions of people swinging between two major emotions: Fear and Greed. Every tick on that screen represents a human decision—someone panicking and selling, or someone getting excited and buying. \n
Technical Analysis (TA) isn't about drawing lines on a screen to predict the future like some kind of fortune teller. It’s the art of hitting the mute button on all the noise—the news, the rumors, the panic, the "expert" opinions—and just watching the movie play out. It's about reading the room, not the spreadsheet. \n
""" , unsafe_allow_html=True)

st.subheader("Market Actions Discounts Everything", divider=True)
st.markdown("***The Insider information is already in the price.***", unsafe_allow_html=True)
st.markdown("""
Now, imaging a company is about to drop a game-changing new product. Maybe it's a new iPhone, or a cure for a disease. You don't know about it yet. The public? Totally in the dark. But the CEO knows. The engineers working late nights know. The suppliers shipping the new parts know.  
And you bet they start buying. Maybe they tell a cousin, or their broker notices something up. It ripples out.  
The stock price starts ticking up. Volume gets heavier as more substantial orders hit the book. The chart makes a "higher low" as aggressive buyers step in. By the time the news finally hits your Twitter feed or the front page of the Wall Street Journal, the price has already moved! The "smart money" is already in, and they're probably getting ready to sell to you.

**The Philosophy:**  
Think about it. Anything and everything that can mess with the price—supply shortages, consumer demand, political drama, inflation data, even the CEO having a bad day—is already baked into the price right now. The market is an incredibly efficient information processing machine. \n

* **Fundamentals** are busy hunting for the "cause" (saying stuff like, "Earnings are up and they beat expectations, so the price should go up!"). Then they get confused when the price drops because the market had already priced that win in weeks ago.
* **Technicians?** We just look at the "effect" ("Price is up and volume is surging? Cool, fundamentals must be fine, I'm buying.").  \n
We honestly don't care why the price is moving. We just care that it’s moving. We trust the wallet votes of the collective market more than we trust a press release. The chart is basically the only insider tip you're ever gonna legally get.
""")

st.subheader("Prices Move in Trends", divider=True)
st.write("***Newton’s First Law of Motion... but for your wallet.***")
st.markdown("""
"A trend in motion stays in motion until acted upon by an equal and opposite force."  \n
This is the toughest lesson for newbies to unlearn. When a crypto coin jumps 100%, your logical brain screams, "It's too high, it has to come down, sell!" When a stock crashes 50%, your bargain-hunter brain says, "It's a steal, it can't go lower, buy!" \n
That’s exactly how you get wrecked. \n
Trends happen because news travels slowly and it takes time for people to really buy in. Psychology shifts gradually, not instantly.  
* **The Stealth Phase**: Insiders and value hunters start buying while the news is still bad. Price creeps up quietly, almost unnoticed.  
* **The Awareness Phase**: The pros and technical traders spot the breakout. Institutional money starts flowing in. Price starts picking up speed and the trend becomes obvious on the chart. 
* **The Mania Phase**: The media catches on. Your taxi driver and grandma start buying because "everyone is getting rich." Price goes vertical! This is usually the end, but it's also where the most explosive moves happen.
""")
st.info("Don't stand in front of a freight train just because you think it's moving **too fast.** It will run you over. Ride that train until it hits a wall.",width="stretch")

st.subheader("History Repeats Itself", divider=True)
st.write("***The Humans haven't updated their firmware in 10,000 years.***")
st.markdown("""
Ever wonder why chart patterns from 1920 look exactly like Bitcoin charts from 2024? Or why the Tulip Mania chart from the 1600s looks just like the Dot Com bubble?  \n
It's because technology changes, algorithms get faster, **but human nature doesn't**.  \n
A "Head and Shoulders" pattern isn't just a random shape chartists made up. It’s a picture of a bunch of buyers trying three times to push the price higher. The middle attempt (the head) is the strongest, but they run out of ammo. The third attempt (the right shoulder) is weak and pathetic. Finally, they get tired and throw in the towel. That sequence—Optimism, Effort, Failure, Surrender—looks the same on a chart whether you’re trading rice in ancient Japan or Tech stocks in Silicon Valley. \n
The chart is just a mirror of human emotion. A "support level" is just a price where investors remember getting a good deal last time. A "resistance level" is just a price where traders remember feeling pain and wanting to get out. If you can read the pattern, you can predict the reaction!


""")

